data.content:
Yes — for simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` instead. It's cleaner and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **complex or computed data** (objects, collections, etc.) that `[DataRow]` can't handle, keep `[DynamicData]` but use tuples for type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData), DynamicDataDisplayName = nameof(GetDisplayName))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
[
    ["valid@email.com", true],
    ["invalid", false],
    ["", false],
];

public static string GetDisplayName(MethodInfo _, object[] data)
    => $"Input: \"{data[0]}\" → {data[1]}";
```

**TL;DR:** Prefer `[DataRow]` for primitive/string args — it's simpler, type-checked at compile time, and gives readable test names automatically. Reserve `[DynamicData]` for when test data must be computed or contains complex types.
